<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Actually it's silly to compare languages that way.  There are French ideas which cannot be easily translated to English and vice-versa.  As a student of French and with a French girlfriend, I've been surprised quite a few times when I asked how to say something and was told that the French don't really say that.<P>To refute your statement though, French being regarded as the language of diplomacy is a direct reflection of that fact that, at one time, France was *the* world power.  To speak French in the courts bespoke a certain nobility, one associated with the greatness of the French nation and its own courts.  This is no longer the case.  France is still a great country (I wouldn't be trying to find a job there if it were not), but it is no longer an overwhelming force in the world.  In fact, no nation is and that is why we are truly beginning to see a global economy emerge.  The dominance of English as a language is based simply on the fact that the US and England both have strong economies.  I'll admit too that the majority of US Americans don't speak another language, and in cases like that sometimes the other person is forced to adapt to us to carry out business.<P>I can agree with you request for better customer service, but I am not sure if EQ is a globally marketed game.  I'll grant that it is played through out the world, but I do not know if VI has specifically modified it so that it is "agreeable" with non-American computers.  Why do I say this?  I have seen many an occasion where a version of software has been changed so that it uses foreign character sets, has all the language translated, etc.  It wouldn't surprise me if there was some sort of disclaimer floating around...<P>Anyway, it seems what you desire, in addition to improved customer service (I think we *all* want that though, don't we?) is a server dedicated to the French language.  But you see, this is already in your power.  The people on a server, not any server rule, will determine what language is spoken there.  If they open a server located in France, while there is a greater likelyhood that mostly European people will play due to the connection speeds, there is no guarantee that the English speaking populace will not.  So what if, theoretically, they opened this server and 75% of the people who played were English-speaking?  Well, most of the conversation on said server would take place in English.  The state of things would only be marginally altered.<P>While it is true that many Europeans are very mutilingual, this is not a hard and fast rule.  There are French people (I know, my girlfriend tutors people in English) who struggle with foreign languages.  If your idea were to become reality, it would only be fair if VI opened a server in each and every country in the world showing a significant  player base.  And I may be wrong, but does France have enough players?  You may not have seen this, but when a server only has 600 people playing it is a very, very lonely place.  Underpopulation can be as great a problem as overpopulation.<P>If what you are requesting is, instead, a European-based server - am I mistaken in thinking that there already is one in existence?  I might point out that in this case you still have the language problems.  Many people will speak different languages, and in this case you will be forced to find a common language to communicate.  It just may end up being English.<P>As a side-note, I may be recalling this incorrectly, but I believe VI may be looking into integrating translation software into EQ?  This way, it wouldn't matter where you are or what language you speak, people should understand you.  Does anyone have any inside information on this, or on the state of translation software?  I cannot help but imagine that this would be a great hassle on the part of VI and very difficult to implement.  Hell, if we have people complaining so often about this problem and that problem and class balance, etc., etc. and VI still hasn't come up with some final solution to quiet everyone, how long will it take them to act upon such an ambitious endeavor as this?<P>BTW, I just wanted to say that English *does* owe a whole, whole lot to the French language.  Our words are derived mostly from Latin and Greek.  There is another source, I forget the exact name of the culture it came from but it has to do with people invading England, possibly linked to Germanic tribes or something similar?  Another source, although it is also derived from Latin, is the French language.  Although the morphemes we use may be recognizable as the Latin morphemes, their form, sound, and spelling are sometimes ripped directly from the French language.<P>Wow, I guess you do learn quite a bit in college after all.<P>My two cents and then some.
</FONT>
