Cerios: <P>Actually, if English is phonetic then that makes many other languages phonetic as well (just by nature of inheritance).  One of the parts of English (and I am seeing this with my nephew who is learning to read now) is that many groups of letters can be pronounced differently based upon what word they are found in.<P>When you claim it is phonetic I imagine all the d00dz who can't spell to save their lives.  And other languages are the exact same way - so many times when chatting with my gf, I've used a word I know how to pronounce, but not necessarily how to spell.  She understands what I mean, but corrects me and we continue.  This can happen in any language really.  But if you really want to go for the phonetic languages, then go for something like Japanese.  "Ka" is always "ka" in Japanese.  The only time odd pronounciations are introduced, really, is when foreign words are adapted to the system of language.<P>Coincidentally, English is not the most commonly spoken language on the planet.  That, my friend, is Chinese, although I am not sure which particular dialect.<P>I like the idea you and Chaleck suggest.  Maybe we should demand VI give us more emotive models and use sign language.  Yeah... I like that idea  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0">
