<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
What I mean when I say English isn't exactly straight-forward is that many combinations of letters have different sounds, not as in a large combination (i.e. a word, although words also have different pronounciations depending on where you travel, and there are some which have different pronounciations even in the same area based on the meaning.<P>Take for example the word "sow": if a noun, it refers to a female pig and rhymes with "cow" (moooo).  If a verb, it means to plant a seed and rhymes with "crow" (caa!).  Same spelling, different meanings, different sounds.<P>What I was referring to was not looking at whole words.  Take for example, the words "book" and "boot".  The "oo" sounds in them are different, even though the words themselves are very similar in spelling.  How is someone who does not speak English supposed to really tell how to pronounce them solely on the merits of how they are spelled?  Unless they have it memorized, chances are they'll get it wrong.
</FONT>
