actually, im not talking about dialects, and i do know latin and classic greek, and i know the difference between an english major and a linguist, i also know that i have a linguist component to my english major.  think of this examples<BR>breathe the verb and breath the noun  the th sound is different in each word<BR>or read (present tense) and read (past tense) they are spelled exactly the same with the exact same letter patterns but are pronounced different in every single dialect.  that proves in itself that every letter combination can be pronounced differently.  if there is even one exception to that rule, it is thrown out, i just gave you two exceptions.<P>where did you hear this, because 2nd graders learn homonyns and they also dispute your theory.  <IMG SRC="rolleyes.gif" border="0"><P>--------------------<P>Auroradae<BR>20th Cleric of Tunare<BR>Karana<BR>Member of Void Of Chaos
